DOMAIN 4: Urban Housing Markets and Spatial Dimensions
SEARCH_DATE: 2025-11-13
PAPERS_FOUND: 12
GEOGRAPHIC_FOCUS: Germany (Berlin, Munich, Hamburg), Europe
SEARCH_SOURCES: Google Scholar, urban studies journals, DIW Berlin, real estate research
====================================================================

DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain examines urban housing dynamics, city-level rent variation, rising housing costs
in German cities, gentrification, displacement, and spatial dimensions of housing affordability.
Focus on Berlin, Munich, and Hamburg as high-cost urban markets. Research documents that rents
in major German cities (A-cities) increased 70% from 2011-2024, with particularly sharp rises
post-2010. Urban-rural divide shows cities with 2% vacancy vs. 7.6% in eastern rural areas.
Housing supply constraints, construction costs, and migration patterns affect urban burden
distribution. Key question: do median-income households maintain stable burdens despite rising
costs (spatial adjustment) or face increasing burdens?

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
Tests Hypothesis 1 (flat burdens for median income despite rising costs) and Hypothesis 2
(high burdens for low-income urban dwellers). Spatial variation critical for understanding
where housing burden concentrated.

KEY_DEBATES:
- Urban-rural housing cost gradients
- Gentrification and displacement mechanisms
- Housing supply elasticity in German cities
- Rent control effectiveness in tight urban markets
====================================================================
